't realize</span><hr size=1> You can chain counterattack styles when *anyone* sets up the opener on your target.  For example, say you have a tank who's using a shield and happily tanking a mob.  Now, if the tank blocks the mob, anyone can use a combat style that uses block as on opener on that mob if they do it before that mob's next attack.  This is very very nice if you have a highly defensive tank, since they'll be blocking and parrying alot and therefore setting up openers for some rather nice styles.  My bard and my roommate's hero were grouped together the other night and he'd block a mob, and I'd immediately use return blade (uses block as opener) on the mob even though I wasn't the one who blocked it.<br>
<br>
Case in point, a lot of people are complaining that the highest level critical strike style chain requires that the target is parried, yet none of the assassin types get the parry skill.  What they don't realize, is that the assassin doesn't have to be the one that parries the target.  Actually, it'd be bad if we had parry and had to parry it ourselves since that would mean we'd be tanking which is very very bad.  Anyhow, any high level tank worth anything is gonna be pretty decent at parry, which should allow the assassins to use these chains alot in a group.  It just ends up being a group only combat style, really, since you have to depend on someone else setting up the opener for you.  It's kind of funny since a lot of people have been saying that the critical strike line isn't too group friendly since you have to be hidden to use the backstab / perforate artery chains which make them one use per fight abilities; but in the end the critical strike chain gives one of the most group friendly combat styles around.<br>
<br>
